r of 1908,\nI wl 'l \"like hi. place, fl\nI \"\"'I <l\" the Host wc can.\"\nThe terms will be: f\nStrictly Cash on Delivery\nw- E. Herman,\nCO.\nALL KINDS\u2019.\n\u25a0bBIPHoKE BLUE 814.\nMrs. J. J. Montgomery Is reported\nvery ill.\nK. I*. Johnson, Notary Public and 1\nConveyancer.\nWanted.\u2014Washing and ironing.\n4U2 Mils. llakuy Biik h. j\nWill Kaiser was on board No. .'1\nTuesday morning bound for Pueblo.\nBolts*.\u2014-To Mr. and Mrs. Reuben\nEarnest on Wednesday f last week,\na small boy.\nMiss Caseley, of Colorado Springs,\nan aunt of Dr. W. P. Woods, arrived\nMonday and will spend the summer\nIn Ordway.\nM. F. Winfree returned from Cali\nfornia last Friday. He was not very\nfavorably impressed with the business\noutlook in the far west.\nBohn.\u2014Monday, May 25th, to Mr.\nand Mrs. George Riley, a line girl.\nTills makes the third honie-blesser for\nthese hapyy parents.\nDr. C. O. Metzlcr, Dentist, Offlrc\nwest of Hotel Berendo. East Ter\nrace, Phone Blue 512.\nThe Ladies\u2019 Union of the Christian\nchurch will serve ice cream and cake\nDecoration Day, afternoon and even\ning, in the old Cash Bazaar room. 3t 10\nAn error in the program for tomor\nrow has been corrected for this issue.\nRev. Stein met/, delivers the oration of\nthe day and Rev. Rice closes the ser\nvice.\nThe warrants stolen from I* red\nCook\u2019s house were found by Will Cook\nin a sand pile near the railroad. Mrs.\nCook's watch and lodge money are\nstill In circulation.\nThe school children covered them\nselves with glory at their home talent\nplay Friday night, each and every par\nticipant, doing exceedingly well for\ntheir first appearance before the foot\nlights.\nM. G. McKee, a brother-in-law of\nIt. L. Martin, arrived Saturday for a\nshort visit,. He Is engaged in the\nbanking business in Oklahoma, and\nleft Tuesday for home to look after\nInterests that were threatened by the\nrecent Mood.\nThe Crawford Entertainers played\nto good houses here Tuesday and\nWednesday nights. They put on a\nclean show, and an exceptionally good\none for three people to produce Ev\neryone seemed to get- their moneys\nworth and will welcome the troupe on\nits return date In the Fall.\nThe Thimble Club met with Mrs.\nEdna GrifTin on Wednesday of this\nweek. The occasion was a farewell to\nMrs. C. It. Wldiilim, wl\u00bb> I VC3 s 1 1\nfor Homer, Illinois, the future home\nof the Wltwlne family. Diirlnn the\nafternoon Mrr. Wluuln\u00dfwae presented\nwith a souvenir spoon, a \u00abI from the\nClub, and a token of the esteem In\nwhich she Is held by Its members.\nDelicious refreshments were served\nh\u00bb \u00bbha HnaiAAM ere the guests departed.\nTHE ORDWAY NEW ERA.\nLARSEN-FREEMAN\nMarried, in the Evangelical parson-\nI age, Tuesday. May 201 li. 190 S, by the\npastor, C. S. Stcinmctz. Mr. Eliot N.\nFreeman,son of Dr. and Mrs. Freeman,\nland Miss Alta L. Larsen.\nMr. Freeman and Miss Larsen have\nj bad charge of King Center school\nI during tiie past year and have received\nmany compliments for the way in\nI which school lias been conducted.\nMr. Freeman lias been chosen as\nteacher of ihc Oiney school and iliev\nwill make their home in Olucy at\nleast for the coming year.\nNotice of Dog Tax\nj All owners of dogs are hereby noti\nfied that the annual dog tax of SI.OO\n1 per head is now due and payable at\nthe Clerk's office. E. P. Johnson.\nTown Clerk.\n1 For Salk. \u2014Sweet Potato and\ni Tomato plants. Ciias. llknslku.\nPhone White 123.\nW. W. Masliburn was in Pm M\nTuesday making arrangements 'or\nsoft drinks to supply Ills patron- n\nthe pool ball, the Fowler lioltliug\nworks being unable to keep up with\ntheir orders for soda pop.\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Kearney returned\nfrom their honeymoon Saturday and\nentertained Hie customary chlvaree\nt party In the evening. They have gone\nto housekeeping in the Joe Gayetty\nhouse on Colorado Boulevard.\nMrs. C. C. Kelley went to Pueblo\nTuesday and while there witnessed\nthe graduating exercises a t the\nMlnnequa Hospital. Five nurses were\ngraduated from the Institution, among\nthem Miss Erickson, whose parents\nreside a few miles west of Ordway.\nj. n Hinze, who was operated on at\nRocky Ford, two weeks ago tomorrow,\nreturned home last Saturday, very\nmuch improved but a little weak. He\nwas under the Influence of the chloro\nform but fifty-eight minutes. We are\nglad to bear of the success of the\noperation.\u2014Fowler Tribune.\nThe real estate business in Ordway\nis never at a stand still. Winfree\nBros, tills week transferred to Oliver,\nHarriet A. and Ernest F. Greene, all\nof block 4 known as the Spindle place\nnear the old artesian well at the north\nunits of town. The purchasers have\nfaith In the future of Ordway, evi\ndently, this being t heir second real es\ntate acquisition since locating here a\nmonth ago.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe desire to return our sincere\nthanks to the many good people of\nOrdway for their acts of kindness and\nwords of sympathy during the sickness\nand death of our husband and father.\nMost especially do wc appreciate the\nassistance rendered by the I. O. O. F.\nM us. Lublla Rutledge\nand Family.\ntown lots for sale\nOn onsv payments. 35 choice lot,\nto select from. I ECi Johnson.\nSelected For Decoration Day\nIn the chill mist of the morning a\nregiment of Infantry IlneH up on its\nDag and looks with anxious eyes upon\na neighboring hilltop aurmounted\nwith breastworks, Jiristling with\nshining riilo barrels, frowning with\nblack muzzled cannon, swarming with\nthe insolent foe. Thither their llag\nmust go. and thither must they fol I\nlow It though that hilltop be the\nmouth of hell. The thousand men\nwho toucli elbows to tile right and\nleft of the Dag are plain American\nboys, they are boys with fathers and\nmothers buck in the homes from\nwhence they came. They do not\nswagger r lioast. The order comes,\nI \u2018\u2019Guide on the colors, march,\u201d and\nthe line sweeps onward. Over the\nditch, up t|ie -llppery banks into the\nswarming masses of the enemy, men\ndrop and the line shortens every step.\nThe color bearer falls, hut before the\n(lag touches the ground another loyal\nhand bears it aloft. Like reeds before\nlie tempest the enemy is beaten\ndown, and then the D:-g Duals in\ntriumph. Greater love, hath no man\nthan this that lie gave his life for\nthat which he lovetli. One by one we\nj are passing away. Our crowning glory\nwill come after we have passed from J\nI this life when it. will be said of us,\nthat we fought to uphold Old Glory.\nDECORATION DAY\nYoung men and old men, everyone\nwill want a new but, a nice pair of\noxfords, or some snappy things in\nfurnishings. Come and let us Six you\nout. Cash Bazaar.\nA Fowlerlte, bearing that one of the\nFowler liverymen bad purchased a new\nhearse, and wishing to play a joke on\n1 him, called W. F. Mooney up over the\nj phone, one day this week, and giving\na fictitious name, tried to hire the\nhearse and a driver for a funeral the\nnext day. The liveryman being some\nwhat absent minded, replied, \u201cSay. I\nour hearse was delayed on the road,\nand won\u2019t be here for about a week, 1\nInit we will send it up as sunn as it\ncomes.\u201d \u2014Fowler Tribune.\nO. P. RUTLEDGE\nAftora period of sulTering extend\ning over several weeks, O. I*. Rutledge\nI departed this life on Saturday after\nj noon at four o'clock.\nThe deceased was 54 years of ago and\nl leaves a wife and three sons to mourn\nI lie loss of a loving husband and\nj father.\nServices at the house were conduct\ned bv the Odd Fellows, Rev. Stcin\n-1 mHz assisting, and tin* remains were\nshipped to Haywood, Illinois, for in\nterment- on Monday.\nCHURCH OF CHRIST\nSunday. May .list, 1908.\nSunday School at 10 o\u2019clock, C. II\nGreen, Supt. Lesson Subject, \u201cJesus\nRisen from the Dead.\u201d\nTeacher Training class at 7:00 p. m.\nTills congregation w ill Join in the\nunion service at the Evangelical\nchurch in the evening.\nEveryone Is cordially invited tc* at\ntend these services.\nRout. 11. Nkwton, Pastor.\nBaptist Church Services.\nSunday School at 10 a. ni.\nSermon at 11 a. m. Subject, 4 Chris\ntian Consistency.\u201d\nYoung People\u2019s Meeting 7:00 p. in.\nSubject, \u201cThe Glory of the True Zion.\u201d\nLeader, W. A. Kane.\nThe evening service will be a union\nmeeting at the Evangelical church on\naccount of the Baccalaureate sermon\nPrayer meeting, 8:00 p. m. Wcdnes\nday evening.\nWe extend to all a cordial invita\ntion to attend these services.\nA. M. Craven, Pastor.\nEvangelical Church Services.\nServices over Sunday as follows;\nSunday School, English and German\nat 10 a. m.\nServices at 11:00 a. in.\nYoung People\u2019s Alliance at 7:00 p. m.\nBaccalaureate Address, 8 p. in.\nMid-week prayer meeting Wednes\nday at 8:00 p. in.\nBob Creek Sunday School at 10 a. tn.\nPreaching at 11 a in.\nKing Center preaching at .'I p. m.\nThe public cordially invited to these\nservices.\nC. S. Steinmktz.\nServices at the Methodist Episcopal\nChurch.\nSunday, May 31, 1908.\nSunday School, 10:00 a. m.. J. J.\nDuncan, Supt. Subject of lesson,\nJesus Risen from the Dead,\u201d John\n18: 1 18.\nMorning service 11 a. m. Rev.\nKepliart, Denver, Colo., will speak In\nthe Interest of the Anti Saloon League\nJunior Epworth League, 3:00 p. m.\nTopic, \u201cPure Heart,\u201d Matt. 5: 8.\nEpworth League devotional service,\n7:00 p. m. Topic, \u201cThe City for\nChrist,\u201d Matt. 21: 10: Zccli. 8: I*B.\nLeaders Mrs. I). C. Roberts and Mrs.\nB. R. Thompson.\nUnion service at Evangelical church\nBaccalaureate sermon by Rev. C. S.\nStclnmetz.\nMid-week service Wednesday even\ning at 7 p. ra.\nA cordial welcome awaits you to all\nthese services. i\nA. W. Rice, Pastor. J\nPlant Trees Crown By Irrigation!\nfrom the\nCOLORADO NURSERY CO.,\n27 Years at Loveland, Colo.\nJ. W. FARRIS, General Agent.\nAll Stock Superior to that Grown East\nALOORE OAFE\nIs A First-Class Short Order\n3r House. Give us a trial and\nsee if wc can\u2019t prove it.\nBLIZZARD RICE.\n3)\n